label.value: decreased microtubule bundle formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of microtubule bundle formation, which normally results in a parallel arrangement of microtubules, is decreased.

label.value: long actin cables

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells form actin cables that are longer than normal.

label.value: sensitive to camphor

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to camphor. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of camphor that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: normal polyphosphate catabolism during cellular response to phosphate starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the breakdown of polyphosphate is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to phosphate starvation.

label.value: normal polyphosphate biosynthesis during cellular response to replete phosphate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the biosynthesis of polyphosphate is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to replete phosphate.

label.value: increased protein localization to medial cortical node

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortical nodes is increased in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal histone binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of histone binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is abnormal. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself binds one or more methylated histone(s) differently from wild type, or that a mutation in one gene affects methylated histone binding by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: decreased histone H3 binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of histone H3 binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: decreased histone H4 binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of histone H4 binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abnormal DNA replication-dependent nucleosome assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the formation of nucleosomes on newly replicated DNA is abnormal.

label.value: resistance to oxidative stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show decreased sensitivity to oxidative stress.

definition.value: Use this term if you have assayed growth of cells exposed to osmotic stress in culture. If you have assayed the response to osmotic stress at the subcellular or molecular level, consider annotating to 'abnormal cellular response to osmotic stress' (FYPO:0000193).

label.value: increased duration of nuclear fusion during mating

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of karyogamy involved in conjugation with cellular fusion is longer than normal.

label.value: abnormal microtubule-based movement

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which microtubule-based movement is abnormal.

label.value: decreased microtubule sliding

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of microtubule sliding, i.e. movement of one microtubule along another microtubule, is decreased.

label.value: abolished protein localization to cell cortex during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell cortex does not occur during the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to cell cortex during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell cortex does not occur during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to cell cortex during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell cortex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished microtubule attachment to cell cortex

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the attachment of microtubules to the cell cortex does not occur.

label.value: normal microtubule bundle formation during mitotic spindle assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which microtubule bundle formation that takes place as part of mitotic spindle assembly, and which normally results in a parallel arrangement of microtubules, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal number of nuclei in ascus

value.value: A phenotype an ascus contains four nuclei, as in wild type.

definition.value: Note that in this phenotype, spores may or may not form normally around the four nuclei.

label.value: normal cell cortex morphology during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, and structure of the cell cortex are normal during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division. The cell cortex is the region of a cell that lies just beneath the plasma membrane.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal cell cortex organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal cell cortex morphology. This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: stationary phase viability unaffected by micafungin

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which the proportion of cells in the population remains viable after entering stationary phase does not change in the presence of micafungin. Normally, wild-type cell populations survive longer in the presence of micafungin than in its absence.

definition.value: Although each cell has a replicative lifespan in that it divides a certain number of times and then dies, replicative lifespan is often measured at the population level, where it is defined by the number of generations at which 50% of the starting cells are dead.

label.value: decreased mitotic checkpoint complex binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of mitotic checkpoint complex binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to kinetochore during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the kinetochore of a chromosome is abnormal during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found at the kinetochore and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to plasma membrane at cell division site during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the plasma membrane surrounding the cell division site is abolished during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to plasma membrane at cell division site during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the plasma membrane surrounding the cell division site is abolished during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to medial cortex during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortex of a cell is abolished during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to medial cortex during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortex of a cell is abolished during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: mislocalized protein distributed in cell cortex during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein is detected abnormally distributed throughout the cell cortex during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle. The protein may normally be restricted to part of the cell cortex, or not normally located in the cell cortex at all.

definition.value: This term can be used for protein that do not normally localize to discrete cytoplasmic regions, or for proteins that do normally show punctate localization but with such localization increased in a mutant. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: mislocalized protein distributed in cell cortex during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein is detected abnormally distributed throughout the cell cortex during mitosis. The protein may normally be restricted to part of the cell cortex, or not normally located in the cell cortex at all.

definition.value: This term can be used for protein that do not normally localize to discrete cytoplasmic regions, or for proteins that do normally show punctate localization but with such localization increased in a mutant. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to cell division site during mitotic anaphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the site of cell division is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during anaphase of mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased cytoplasmic microtubule depolymerization at plus end at cell tip

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cytoplasmic microtubule depolymerization, i.e. the removal of tubulin dimers from a cytoplasmic microtubule, occurs to a lesser extent than normal at the plus end of the microtubule at the cell tip. Normally, rapid depolymerization takes place when the growing plus end of the microtubule reaches the cell tip.

label.value: increased protein kinase activity during mitotic interphase

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is increased during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: increased protein kinase activity during mitosis

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is increased during mitosis.

label.value: abnormal cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is abnormally arrested at the mitotic G2/M phase transition during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: increased cellular reactive oxygen species level during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of reactive oxygen species (ROS) measured in a cell is higher than normal during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

label.value: decreased cellular heme level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of any heme measured in the cell is lower than normal.

label.value: normal growth on sampangine

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing sampangine.

label.value: sensitive to sampangine

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to sampangine. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of sampangine that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: increased sister chromatid cohesion along chromosome arms during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is increased along the length of the chromosome arms during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: increased duration of Rad52 focus presence during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which sites at which the protein Rad52 accumulates remain present for longer than normal.

label.value: abolished spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which rapid, back-and-forth movement of the mitotic spindle pole body (SPB), and associated chromosome movement, do not occur. Normally, SPB oscillation occurs during mitotic interphase (as well as prophase) but is restricted to a small space.

label.value: small fragmented mitochondria

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitochondria are smaller than normal.

label.value: mitochondria present in increased numbers

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell contains more mitochondria than normal.

label.value: large mitochondria

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitochondria are larger than normal.

label.value: decreased mitochondrial fission

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitochondrial fission, the division of a mitochondrion into two or more separate compartments, occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: increased mitochondrial fission

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitochondrial fission, the division of a mitochondrion into two or more separate compartments, occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: normal mitotic centromeric sister chromatid cohesion

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between centromeres of sister chromatids is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased splicing of mRNA introns with nonconsensus cis-splicing sequences

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of mRNA splicing via the spliceosome of introns that have one or more deviations from optimal cis-splicing sequences is decreased. Nonconsensus features may include a longer distance between the branch point and 3' splice site, lacking a polypyrimidine tract, or use of alternative 5' splice sites.

label.value: aggregated actin cortical patches during mitotic interphase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin cortical patches cluster together more than normal during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.
